		  ( N'Family cooking under coronavirus: I have become a chef with two grumpy regular customers'' Family cooking under coronavirus: I have become a chef with two grumpy regular customers'
			, -- Title - nvarchar(500)
            N'Illustration: NÃ©stor Feijoo/The Observer â€˜If thereâ€™s been a focal point so far, it was my eldest daughterâ€™s seventh birthday. Thereâ€™s be no party, no friends, fewer presents but I could still make her a cake.â€™ Illustration: NÃ©stor Feijoo/The Observer'
			, -- Short Description - nvarchar(500)
            N'Cooking and clearing up has been relentless â€“ and thatâ€™s without adding a special birthday cake to my range of signature dishes<br> <span itemscope="""" itemtype=""http://schema.org/Person"" itemprop=""author"">
<a rel=""author"" class=""tone-colour"" itemprop=""sameAs"" data-link-name=""auto tag link"" href=""https://www.theguardian.com/profile/timlewis""><span itemprop=""name"">Tim Lewis</span></a></span> <time itemprop=""datePublished"" datetime=""2020-05-17T15:00:02+0100"" data-timestamp=""1589724002000"" class=""content__dateline-wpd js-wpd"">
Sun 17 May 2020 <span class=""content__dateline-time"">15.00&nbsp;BST</span>
</time> <span class=""drop-cap""><span class=""drop-cap__inner"">I</span></span>â€™m sitting down to write this having just cleaned fox poo out of the tiny grooves in the soles<strong> </strong>of my four-year-oldâ€™s sandals. She also, somehow, smeared it all over her legs, her dress, my legs, my shorts. The only plus I can take from it is that, for once in our crowded corner of south London, social distancing was not an issue. Of course, even in non-coronavirus times, 98% of anecdotes about young children end in someone being covered in something or other. But for many parents â€“ at which point I insert an enormous caveat to make it clear that Iâ€™m talking about those who havenâ€™t been infected, or made redundant, and arenâ€™t frontline workers, and are extremely lucky enough to still be operating in a strange bubble of â€œnormalâ€<strong> </strong>â€“<strong> </strong>Iâ€™d suspect that the greatest challenges of the past few weeks, and moments of profoundest despair, have come in the kitchen. Cooking for your children can be a dispiriting experience. Thereâ€™s often a magical window when they are around two, where they eat all sorts of exotic things: green vegetables, non-white food generally, Italian dishes that donâ€™t begin with â€œpâ€. But gradually, imperceptibly, I have found my kids becoming entrenched in their tastes, suspicious of the unfamiliar. Iâ€™m not talking about olives and kimchi; just getting them to eat some courgette involves agreeing to a Peppa Pig all-nighter in return. Not long ago, but BC (before coronavirus), I was moaning to a colleague about it, a serious home cook, a tweezers-and-soda-siphon guy. Also, his children are older, teenagers. I wanted to know if it got any easier. â€œYou have to think of it like being a line cook,â€ he replied, years of pain in his voice. Your job is not to be showy. Itâ€™s to do your bit and get the job done: to make peace with cooking the same meal again and again. Innovation or experimentation were neither expected nor required from your customers (that is, your offspring). I have<strong> </strong>thought about this conversation from time to time after coronavirus took hold, and especially since the schools closed in March, when two major changes became apparent. First, demand: I went from having to supply my children not with two meals a day, but three, plus morning and afternoon snacks (though they helpfully remind me of snack-time by growing fangs and clawing at the fridge, without fail, at 11am and 3pm). The other disruption was supply. Just before we realised how serious the pandemic was, my girlfriend and I raised our eyebrows at friends who went to Asda at 7am on a Sunday morning to stock up. Within days, we were flooded with images of whole aisles of supermarkets cleared out. Toilet roll went first, then pasta, rice, flour, tinned tomatoes. You know all this. The experience of seeing this unfold did, I understand looking back, send me a bit mad. Itâ€™s a clichÃ© (most things about parenthood are) but when you have children itâ€™s hard not to become convinced that your main responsibility now â€“ perhaps the only thing that really matters â€“ is to keep them alive and well. Coronavirus may have made this more real and present than usual for me, but in truth itâ€™s hardwired. Iâ€™m happier when my kids have eaten well, secure in the knowledge that whatever else Iâ€™m getting wrong, that part Iâ€™m not screwing up. I didnâ€™t stockpile or panic buy â€“ not particularly for moral reasons but, in part, because weâ€™ve only got a small freezer and limited shelf space. But I did find myself checking the websites of online shopping companies obsessively: first thing in the morning, my last act before bed, and some days a dozen times in between. I should add here that the online food suppliers and their delivery drivers have done an incredible job of reorganising their systems and keeping things as smooth as they could. My children will never know, or appreciate, how close they came to <em>two days in a row</em> without bananas. Many days, cooking and clearing up after the kids has<strong> </strong>felt like a full-time job (actually worse: it starts at 7am, goes on till past 10pm, and you donâ€™t get half an hour to mull over the perfect phrasing of an email). It is<strong> </strong>exhausting, relentless and relentlessly thankless, as any parent without additional childcare in the normal run of things already knows well. Iâ€™ve been, frankly, astonished at my kidsâ€™ inability to sit at a table for longer than 4.5 seconds without breaking out into song, or wrestling each other, or nipping to their bedroom to get something â€œvery importantâ€ like a small piece of string, or a plastic fish, or a Sylvanian Families Halloween slide set (donâ€™t ask). In order to speed up the four-year-oldâ€™s eating, my girlfriend has invented a game in which she pretends to be a toothbrush (from Texas, I think) who wants nothing more than to â€œstopâ€ our daughter having any more dinner (full rules available on request), which is ultimately very effective but also makes me want to jump out of the window. But as time goes on, Iâ€™ve started to make my peace with the situation.<strong> </strong>Accepting my role as, in Bill Bufordâ€™s words, a kitchen slave, I listen more to what my kids want to eat, rather than bending them to my will. Feeling consulted, they seem to become more open to trying things. Some dinners have been disasters â€“ an attempt to pitch aubergine parmigiana as â€œpizza without the crustâ€ didnâ€™t fly â€“<strong> </strong>but the next morning they just eat a double breakfast. And itâ€™s made me more resourceful: we found a huge patch of wild garlic in a nearby wood, and the kids just about tolerated the pesto we made with it. I dug out various packets of dried pulses from the back of the cupboard, one of which had a best-before date of 2015 and I could only cook by putting instructions through Google Translate, but which were, nonetheless, delicious. On the radio, I heard someone compare life during coronavirus to being on a cruise ship: the three meals provided a structure to a day that otherwise might be disconcertingly free and unhinged. As the weeks became a month, weâ€™ve tried to differentiate the days, or at least the weekends. Sunday night is dress-up dinner night: we do it not to be la-di-da so much as to ensure that our tracksuit bottoms donâ€™t wear out from overuse. <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/food/baking"" data-link-name=""auto-linked-tag"" data-component=""auto-linked-tag"" class=""u-underline"">Baking</a> kills time and we do some of that: banana bread, soda bread, lots of biscuits. The kids are<strong> </strong>interested for around a minute and a half, drift off, and return to lick the spoons. I havenâ€™t<strong> </strong>made sourdough, unlike everyone else on social media apparently, mainly because itâ€™s too much of a faff, but also because I havenâ€™t got over my Electra complex of killing my â€œmotherâ€ back in 2017. If thereâ€™s been a focal point so far, it was my eldest daughterâ€™s seventh birthday, which fell on Easter Sunday. Obviously thereâ€™d be no party, no friends, fewer presents, but I <em>could</em><em> </em>still make her a cake. When I asked her what kind, she requested â€œmint choc chipâ€ with â€œmarshmallowsâ€, which sounded totally disgusting, but which turned out â€“ by some miracle or misfortune â€“ to match the exact description of grasshopper pie, from <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2012/apr/22/christina-tosi-milk-bar-interview"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">Christina Tosiâ€™s </a><em>Momofuku Milk Bar</em> cookbook. Itâ€™s a book Iâ€™ve never previously cooked from, because every recipe contains so many sections that even reading it is exhausting, but if ever there were a time when you conceivably could spend three days baking it was now. (Plus it only required 40g of flour, which was all we had.) At 3pm on my daughterâ€™s birthday, we lit seven candles and brought it out.<strong> </strong>Watching her eating her brown, sludgy dream-cake seemed to put her gag reflex well and truly to the test, but she made polite noises, ate a slice, and we put the rest in the freezer, where we will probably rediscover it in 10 yearsâ€™ time. Of course, the cake didnâ€™t really matter. It was just one of hundreds of meals we will<strong> </strong>make during this strange period. Many people are asking themselves how their lives will change after lockdown. I hope I will be more relaxed about cooking for myself and others, appreciative of and resourceful with what we have. As for cooking the same meals over and over again, Iâ€™ve decided that Iâ€™m not going to think of myself as a line cook. Instead, Iâ€™m recasting myself as a chef with a small range of signature dishes â€“ macaroni cheese, pizza, fish fingers â€“ and a couple of grumpy regulars who are, nonetheless, fiercely loyal. â€¦ just when we need it the most. The Guardianâ€™s honest, authoritative, fact-based reporting has never mattered more. As we face the biggest challenge of our lifetimes, weâ€™ll remain with you, so we can all better understand and combat the crisis. But at this crucial moment, news organisations are facing an existential threat. With advertising revenues plummeting, we risk losing a major source of our funding. More than ever before, we need your support to help fill the gap.  Youâ€™ve read <span class=""epic-article-count__normal"">9</span> articles in the last six months. We believe everyone deserves to read quality news and measured explanation, in times of crisis and beyond. Thatâ€™s why we keep our journalism free from a paywall and open to everyone â€“ something enabled only by reader support. Youâ€™re now visiting in your millions, and supporting us from 180 countries around the world.  We have upheld our editorial independence in the face of the disintegration of traditional media. Free from commercial ownership and political bias, our journalism is never influenced by billionaire owners or shareholders. Our agenda and opinions are our own, and this makes us different. It means we can challenge the powerful without fear â€“ investigating, disentangling and interrogating.  We need your support so we can keep delivering open, independent journalism. Every contribution, however big or small, helps secure our long term future.  <strong><span class=""contributions__highlight"">Support the Guardian from as little as $1 â€“ and it only takes a minute. Thank you.</span></strong>  We will use this to send you a single email in July 2020. To find out what personal data we collect and how we use it, please visit our <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/help/privacy-policy"">Privacy Policy</a> <a href=""https://profile.theguardian.com/signin?INTCMP=DOTCOM_COMMENTS_SIGNIN"" class=""_underline_1lj47_3"">Sign in</a> or <a href=""https://profile.theguardian.com/register?INTCMP=DOTCOM_COMMENTS_REG"" class=""_underline_1lj47_3"">create your Guardian account</a> to join the discussion. The Chinese use the same word for crisis as they do for opportunity. As such both of my kids can not only now use a chip pan but they know how to smother a chip pan fire with a damp tea towel. I spend much time cooking now. There are 3 adults in our house, my husband and myself who are vegan and my 27 yo daughter who has Crohn''s and is on a strict diet ... pretty much opposite to ours. So I do 2 main meals. My husband is now concerned he is overweight so wants to eat at lunchtime. I hate eating at lunchtime. So 3 different main meals. He is actually working from home, whilst I am ''working'' from home ie answering a few token emails occasionally and sitting in the garden. <br>In all honesty I don''t mind, I was a product of the 80s where anything but massive career and financial success was viewed as failure, but I have always preferred to be at home with my family. Very much a mother hen. Sadly, we have to afford to eat so I have always had to work. But being at home in lockdown has only emphasised that feeling and I do struggle to see myself returning ... priorities have changed. We arenâ€™t really eating any differently - always cook from scratch. The weirdest thing is that with a child returning; there are three of us 22, 24 and 52; Iâ€™m certain Iâ€™m cooking far less. Cooking is an easy way to be creative after a day of Work via video chats I am in lockdown with my husband - who deals with stress by cooking. My 2 adult sons have moved back in with us - they both love to cook as well. It has all got very competitive. I haven''t needed to cook for 8 weeks. I am also getting fat!! Really? We are finding our children are much happier with meals cooked from scratch from fresh vegetables and other produce than they were when we relied on the weekly supermarket shop. Rather than watch the seemingly endless cookery programs on TV we''ve gone back to trying out recipes from the several shelves of cookery books we''ve bought or been given over the years. Turns out its cheaper too! I''m the cook in our house and I''m totally sick of eating my own food. The kids however don''t seem to mind it. We are having roast pork tonight - I have explained to the kids it is what sausages are made out of to convince them to eat it.<br> <br>Making pack lunches whether they are in or not during the week has been a godsend. Especially with the price of Lidl crisps, juice cartons and ''tracker'' bars. By getting exercised about what your children eat, you are literally handing them power over you on a plate. Cook reasonably healthy meals most of the time, serve them without negotiation, and do not offer alternatives. If they are hungry, they will eat it. If they don''t, don''t show any sign of being upset. That way, food is no longer a power lever for them. Have sandwiches for lunch and cereal or toast for breakfast, so you only cook once a day. Don''t let them snack too much, otherwise they won''t eat meals. Don''t fall for middle class ideas that what your children eat (olives, polenta, avocado, whatever) is a measure of your worth as a person or a parent. It isn''t. I find this so odd, but perhaps I should just think my lucky stars. I was never this kind of eater, nor was my sister, nor is my niece â€“ was it something my mother and then we did right or is it perhaps a familial trait at a genetic level? We always had new and interesting things to try as kids, the rule was that we had to give it a fair try and then if we didnâ€™t like it we really didnâ€™t have to eat it. The same at restaurants â€“ my mom would usually order something predictably pleasing and I would get to pick something exotic that sounded interesting, and then if I didnâ€™t like it we would trade dishes. Weâ€™ve done that with my niece and she remains willing to try damn near anything â€“ and the things she hasnâ€™t liked in the past, like very spicy food, sheâ€™ll still try a bite of to see if sheâ€™s â€œgotten to like it.â€œ As I said, for all I know itâ€™s genetic and nothing weâ€™re doing right. I''m in my mid 60s and it became apparent to my mum, that I was a fussy eater, when we moved to Liverpool, when I was 8. Before that we lived in North Wales. Main meal of the day, at home, bar Sunday was bacon and potatoes. In Liverpool we had choice and I had a whole load of foods that I could refuse. Oddly enough I loved all vegetables, liver and kidneys. I was fine, once I hit puberty, then I would eat anything. Kids know re food, they have a great deal of power. My wife''s quite fussy, I''ve developed ruses like. Describing a dish as North African, when it''s Indian. Thin sliced courgettes, dip in flour then in beaten egg and then flour again and shallow fry. Touch of salt. It appears that when a child approaches 27 the hinges on the doors of dishwashers, washing machines and the like stop working for them. Who knew? 27? Are you sure about that? 100% I thought it was 15.... Kids grow out of it. My younger one complained at age 7, without any irony - ''I haven''t had any bad food today !''. We found the trick was to find a vegetable and fruit that they would eat and give them that - frozen peas or whatever (after being thawed !). He''s a healthy eater now at 21 - they''ll come to no harm most times. What a bizarre article and its lament. I am not trying to be deliberately contrary but even at the best of times, with or without the VIRUS, we all need to eat. So what has changed? U Kids were at school for lunch, possibly also eating at breakfast and/or after school club too. The Author has just realised what a pain in the Aris household chores and childcare can be.<br>Fortunately, I live in a household where we all knew this already, and I''ve been doing the majority of the cooking for years, so lockdown''s not been too much of a culture shock for us. But we could never afford school lunch so my mom made us sandwiches every day. And she was workingâ€¦ Admittedly, we would go out to restaurants on a regular basis. Such a challenge. I recall my aunt serving the midday meal for a threshing crew of five hard labouring men plus four or more kids. The food was superb (mostly home grown), with everything organized and on time. Hard to imagine how she did it all, but she took it in stride. And no one would have put up with kids whinging and whining about the fare. Luxury. Tell young un''s today we were confined to a modest 4 ensuite Thames riverside yarn conversion in Maidenhead with Oat Ham otter lentils and strained leftovers from Heston Bloomingtroll Services, washed down with Fappachinose My grandmother was a farmer''s wife. She had to cook for her immediate family, step family members and farm labourers. My mum used to wax lyrically on what a good cook her mum was. I tactlessly suggested the gift hadn''t been passed down. Mum said, her mother didn''t have the luxury of time; to teach her two daughters how to cook. Mum and her younger sister did the jobs, our nain couldn''t do. Looking after the younger brothers, house work, feeding the farm animals. Iâ€™ve been lucky enough to be able to decide what I would like to have for supper then go out and buy it then cook it <br>Iâ€™ve changed now and Iâ€™m shopping every 2 weeks , using up every bit I buy and saving loads I seriously think that my overriding memory of lockdown will be the relentless emptying of the dishwasher. Think of those of us who don''t have one... You have my sympathy. Mine broke and it nearly tipped me over the edge - it''s bad enough with a dishwasher finding 17 cups in your teenagers bedroom just after you''ve cleared up the kitchen. Luckily my OH managed to fix it. Yes!!! Ours was only used every few days, but now it seems to be on daily!! My path is a pathway for a fox. It''s nice to see it when it appears. Foxy. I bought two packets of prawn noodles and was just about to eat them last night when the ash of my cigarette fell in, the juice.. I still managed to eat the though and nearly all the juice. I''m still disappointed I didn''t get to drink all the juice.. Foxes live in our neighbour''s garden. Our dog and another neighbour''s dog are driven nuts on a regular basis by this as they both detest the foxes. One night I was about to let the dog out for his late night patrol when I realised the two foxes were curled up in the garden. He was desperate to get out but I made sufficient noise opening the door slowly for them to escape first. Iâ€™m the only cook in my house &amp; when I cook I have only 1 gear - Hearty grub &amp; lots of it! Normally this is offset by working hours, eating out etc and eating much, much less. But thereâ€™s no escape now. Weâ€™re all eating at the table now which is great but our waistlines are all expanding! Heart, lungs, liver lights and fries , sound offal, the sort of thing a French chef would cover in a sauce . We are eating at the table too, but funnily donâ€™t have masses of new conversation each day <a class=""js-rec-tooltip-link"" href=""https://profile.theguardian.com/signin?INTCMP=DOTCOM_COMMENTS_SIGNIN_RECOMM"">Sign in</a> or <a class=""js-rec-tooltip-link"" href=""https://profile.theguardian.com/register?INTCMP=DOTCOM_COMMENTS_REG_RECOMM"">create your Guardian account</a>to recommend a comment', -- PostContent - nvarchar(max)
