            N'"â€˜Hopefully weâ€™ll come to see the online world as a pandemic toolâ€™: Miranda July. Photograph: Rex/Shutterstock A scene from Kajillionaire. Photograph: Matt Kennedy"' , -- Short Description - nvarchar(500)
            N'"The film-maker on her new movie about con artists, the trials of home-schooling, and the role Roseanne Barr played in her early career <time itemprop=""datePublished"" datetime=""2020-05-17T14:00:02+0100"" data-timestamp=""1589720402000"" class=""content__dateline-wpd js-wpd"">
Sun 17 May 2020 <span class=""content__dateline-time"">14.00&nbsp;BST</span>
</time> <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/film/miranda-july"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">Miranda July</a>, 46, is an acclaimed US film-maker, author and artist. <em>Kajillionaire</em>, her third film, and first for almost a decade, was a hit at Sundance and will be released later this year; her debut, 2005â€™s <em>Me and You and Everyone We Know</em>, is being honoured with a <a href=""https://www.criterion.com/shop"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">Criterion Collection</a> edition. There is also the release of a chunky, eponymous monograph that traces her idiosyncratic creative output, with commentary from the likes of Spike Jonze, Carrie Brownstein and David Byrne. She lives in Los Angeles with the director Mike Mills and their son, Hopper. <strong>How are you coping with lockdown in LA?<br></strong>You know, holding up. Iâ€™m healthy, as is my family. And now weâ€™re a bit more used to this new schedule, wherein I teach my child school instead of that child going to school. <strong>Howâ€™s home-schooling going?<br></strong>Itâ€™s a little worrisome. My childâ€™s only in second grade and, like, the mathâ€¦ My husband walked by us the other day and I had 121 pennies out and we are dividing them into groups of 11, because that was the only way I could think of to figure out if 121 was divisible by 11. He said, â€œWhat are you doing that for? Thereâ€™s other ways.â€ And I was like [whispers], â€œI donâ€™t know them!â€ <strong>A theme in your work is about human connection. Have you thought about what longer-term impact coronavirus might have?<br></strong>I have this fantasy that weâ€™ll somehow think of social media and the online world as pandemic tools after this. Weâ€™ll be so grateful for them: weâ€™ll understand that we were brilliant to have thought of this thing that is going to help us survive the many, many pandemics to come, but that we wonâ€™t feel quite as beguiled by them when thereâ€™s not a pandemic, because weâ€™ll have this association. <em><strong>Kajillionaire</strong></em><strong> is about a family of small-time con artists. Youâ€™ve described it as deeply personal but not autobiographical â€“ what do you mean by that?<br></strong>Well, the characters are fictional. I did not grow up like them, or live like that â€“ itâ€™s more an emotional resonance than any practical thing. At Sundance, a number of people came up and were like, â€œThis is so like my family...â€ And then they would describe something that was actually so unfamiliar to me. So I realised, â€œOK, this is extreme enough that this family could be the unconscious of many different kinds of anxious families.â€ <strong>Is your work ever autobiographical?<br></strong>I have only ever written two things that are biographical or based on my life: <em><a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/film/2012/jan/08/it-chooses-miranda-july-review"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">It Chooses You</a></em>,<em> </em>the book that was about the making of my second movie, and one short story, <em>Itâ€™s Something That Needs Nothing</em><strong> </strong>[which appeared in the <em>New Yorker</em> and her 2007 collection <em><a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/books/2007/jun/30/featuresreviews.guardianreview19"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">No One Belongs Here More Than You</a></em>]. <strong>Tell me about thatâ€¦<br></strong>Itâ€™s sort of about gay love and itâ€™s loosely based on me and my first girlfriend. Whereas with<strong> </strong>none of the other stories can I even say that. Or books or movies. <strong>And yet people often assume your work is autobiographical?<br></strong>Maybe that distinction got kind of blurry for people, because I acted in my first feature â€“ even though all my friends looked at that and were like, â€œJust pure fiction.â€ I think people tend to do that to women anyway, sort of assume that theyâ€™re not conceptualising a whole world from the ground up but theyâ€™re pulling from their diary or something. Thereâ€™s a bit of a bias there. <strong>Thereâ€™s an aside in the new book that you somehow got Roseanne Barrâ€™s FedEx number back in the 1990s and youâ€™d use it to ship things. Was that just what you had to do to make it as an artist?<br></strong>I think very few people <em>have</em> to use <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/culture/roseanne-barr"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">Roseanne Barr</a>â€™s FedEx number for their artwork. In my 20s, my rebellions were not always that enlightened, they were for their own sake. And it maybe took a little while to realise: look how radical you could be in how you do your work, all that energy can go into <em>this</em>. This is a great place for it! <strong>Looking at the new book, it seems you keep everything from your life and work. What was the weirdest thing you found in your archive?<br></strong>Thereâ€™s a man in my neighbourhood, heâ€™s quasi-homeless and I pay him to do different gardening things. Heâ€™s the only person I talk to, other than my family, every day. He also gives me letters and gifts. And Iâ€™ve saved every single thing over 15 years that heâ€™s given me, except for a few things that eventually attracted rats, like boxes of chocolate <strong>What sort of things?<br></strong>A baby blanket, a 56-colour eyeshadow kit, a purse. They are taking up a disproportionate amount of room now, but at a certain point, once you start saving things you canâ€™t stop. Things accrue meaning because theyâ€™re saved, sometimes.<br> <strong>What will you do next?<br></strong>At this point it seems pretty clear that after I make a movie, I write a book. So Iâ€™m writing a novel now; thatâ€™ll be done in many years. <strong>In a strange way, might you have more time now you are stuck at home on lockdown?<br></strong>If I was 25 without kids, that would be the case, but Iâ€™ve barely written at all since the pandemic. But if I wasnâ€™t writing this novel, Iâ€™d be awfully tempted to invent something that could only function at this time. I see people are doing that.<strong> </strong>Thereâ€™s so much anarchistic potential for self-invention and to dismantle all these old-fashioned ways of doing things. Thatâ€™s really interesting to me and, frankly, sort of distracting. I have to not get pulled into that; I have to tell myself: â€œOther people should do that. You should write your novel.â€<br> <span class=""bullet"">â€¢</span> <em>Miranda July</em> is published by Prestel (Â£39.99). To order a copy go to <a href=""https://guardianbookshop.com/miranda-july-9783791385211.html?utm_source=editoriallink&amp;utm_medium=merch&amp;utm_campaign=article"" data-link-name=""in body link"" class=""u-underline"">guardianbookshop.com</a>. Delivery charges may apply â€¦ just when we need it the most. The Guardianâ€™s honest, authoritative, fact-based reporting has never mattered more. As we face the biggest challenge of our lifetimes, weâ€™ll remain with you, so we can all better understand and combat the crisis. But at this crucial moment, news organisations are facing an existential threat. With advertising revenues plummeting, we risk losing a major source of our funding. More than ever before, we need your support to help fill the gap.  Youâ€™ve read <span class=""epic-article-count__normal"">11</span> articles in the last six months. We believe everyone deserves to read quality news and measured explanation, in times of crisis and beyond. Thatâ€™s why we keep our journalism free from a paywall and open to everyone â€“ something enabled only by reader support. Youâ€™re now visiting in your millions, and supporting us from 180 countries around the world.  We have upheld our editorial independence in the face of the disintegration of traditional media. Free from commercial ownership and political bias, our journalism is never influenced by billionaire owners or shareholders. Our agenda and opinions are our own, and this makes us different. It means we can challenge the powerful without fear â€“ investigating, disentangling and interrogating.  We need your support so we can keep delivering open, independent journalism. Every contribution, however big or small, helps secure our long term future.  <strong><span class=""contributions__highlight"">Support the Guardian from as little as $1 â€“ and it only takes a minute. Thank you.</span></strong>  We will use this to send you a single email in July 2020. To find out what personal data we collect and how we use it, please visit our <a href=""https://www.theguardian.com/help/privacy-policy"">Privacy Policy</a>"
